			A very, very likely misconception regarding FFmpeg:

			When you use ffmpeg -n -nostdin and the output file already exists, ffmpeg does NOT convert anything, but still exits with code 0 (success). It logs   some  error messages to stderr, but the exit code tells your script "everything went fine."

			This means:

			for   
			
			

ffmpeg -loglevel repeat+level+48 -n -nostdin -i ./abc123.ts -c copy ./abc123.ts.mp4 && echo "okokokokokokokoko"



			echo "okokokokokokokoko"    will execute — even though nothing was converted
			$? will be 0 — even though the job was skipped
			Any "mark as completed" logic after && will fire — incorrectly

			In batch scripts, this can silently cause thousands of files to be marked as "successfully converted" when they were never touched.

			The currently possible solution is to analyze the information in stderr.

